\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 As for the Egyptian capital, the most likely site is Memphis, the principal seat of government during most of Egypt\'92s history. (See\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/tc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/6"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 MEMPHIS}}.) If this was the case, then the starting point of the\'a0\cb4 \strokec5 Exodus\cb3 \strokec2 \'a0march must have been sufficiently near Memphis for Moses to have been called before Pharaoh after midnight on Passover night and then to have reached Rameses in time to begin the march toward Succoth before the 14th day of Nisan ended. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/51/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 12:29-31,}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/51/1"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 \'a037,}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/51/2"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 \'a041,\'a042}}) The oldest Jewish tradition, recorded by Josephus, is to the effect that the march began a short distance N of Memphis. \'97
\f1\i Jewish Antiquities,
\f0\i0 \'a0II, 315 (xv,\'a01).\
A route through the Wadi Tumilat would be so far to the N of Memphis as to make the above circumstances impracticable. For this reason, many earlier commentators have suggested one of the well-known \'93pilgrim\'94 routes through Egypt, such as the el Haj route leading from Cairo across to Suez (ancient Clysma, later Kolsum) at the head of the Gulf of Suez.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\i\b \cf2 Where was the Red Sea parted to allow Israel to cross over?
\f0\i0\b0 \
It should be noted that, after reaching the second stage of their journey, Etham \'93at the edge of the wilderness,\'94 God ordered Moses to \'93turn back and encamp before Pihahiroth .\'a0.\'a0. by the sea.\'94 This maneuver would cause Pharaoh to believe the Israelites were \'93wandering in confusion.\'94 ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/52/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 13:20;}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/52/1"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 \'a014:1-3}}) Scholars favoring the el Haj route as the likely one point out that the Hebrew verb for \'93turn back\'94 is emphatic and does not mean merely to \'93divert\'94 or \'93turn aside,\'94 but has more the sense of returning or at least of a marked detour. They suggest that, upon reaching a point N of the head of the Gulf of Suez, the Israelites reversed their line of march and went around to the E side of Jebel \uc0\u701 Ataqah, a mountain range bordering the W side of the Gulf. A large host, such as the Israelites were, would find no effective way for swift exit from such a position if pursued from the N, and hence they would be bottled up with the sea blocking their way.\
Jewish tradition of the first century C.E. conveys such a picture. (See\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/tc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/7"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 PIHAHIROTH}}.) But, more importantly, such a situation fits the general picture portrayed in the Bible itself, whereas the popular views of many scholars do not. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/53/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 14:9-16}}) It seems evident that the crossing must have been far enough from the head of the Gulf (or western arm of the Red Sea) that Pharaoh\'92s forces would not have been able simply to circle the end of the Gulf and easily come upon the Israelites on the other side. \'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/54/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 14:22,\'a023}}.\
Pharaoh had changed his mind about the release of the Israelites as soon as he learned of their departure. Certainly the loss of such a slave nation meant a heavy economic blow to Egypt. It would not be difficult for his chariots to overtake this entire nation on the move, particularly in view of their \'91turning back.\'92 Now, encouraged by the thought that Israel was wandering in confusion in the wilderness, he went after them with confidence. With a crack force of 600 chosen chariots, all the other chariots of Egypt mounted with warriors, his cavalrymen, and all his military forces, he came upon Israel at Pihahiroth. \'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/55/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 14:3-9}}.\
Strategically the position of the Israelites looked very bad. They were evidently hemmed in between the sea and the mountains, with the Egyptians blocking the way back. In their apparently trapped position, fear struck the hearts of the Israelites and they began to complain against Moses. Now God stepped in to protect Israel by moving the cloud from the front to the rear. On one side, toward the Egyptians, it was darkness; on the other it kept lighting up the night for Israel. While the cloud held back the Egyptians from attacking, at Jehovah\'92s command Moses lifted his rod, and the seawaters split apart, leaving the dry seabed as a path for Israel. \'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/56/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 14:10-21}}.\

\f2\i\b Width and depth of place of crossing.
\f0\i0\b0 \'a0Since Israel crossed the sea in one night, it could hardly be assumed that the waters parted in a narrow channel. Rather, the channel may have been a kilometer or more in width. Though in fairly close marching formation, such a group, along with what wagons they had, their baggage, and their cattle, even when rather closely ranked, would occupy an area of perhaps 8 sq\'a0km (3 sq\'a0mi) or more. It appears, therefore, that the sea-opening allowed the Israelites to cross on a fairly wide front. If there was about a 1.5-km (1\'a0mi) front, then the depth of the Israelite column would probably be about 5\'a0km (3\'a0mi) or more. If it was about a 2.5-km (1.5\'a0mi) front, the depth might be about 3\'a0km (2\'a0mi) or more. It would take such a column several hours to get into the seabed and travel across it. While they did not go in panic, but maintained their battle formation, they would no doubt move with considerable haste.\
Had it not been for the cloud, the Egyptians would have easily overtaken and slaughtered\'a0
