\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 many. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/57/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 15:9}}) When the Israelites had gone into the sea and the cloud behind them had moved ahead to reveal this fact to the Egyptians, they pursued. Here, again, is emphasized the necessity of considerable breadth and length of dry seabed, for Pharaoh\'92s military force was great. Bent on destruction and recapture of their former slaves, the entire force went well into the seabed. Then, during the morning watch, which ran from about 2:00 to 6:00\'a0a.m., Jehovah looked out from the cloud and began to throw the camp of the Egyptians into confusion, taking the wheels off their chariots. \'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/58/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 14:24,\'a025}}.\
The Israelites, by the approaching of morning, got safely across on the eastern shore of the Red Sea. Then Moses was commanded to stretch his hand out so that the waters would come back over the Egyptians. At this \'93the sea began to come back to its normal condition,\'94 and the Egyptians fled from encountering it. This also would indicate that the waters had opened up widely, for a narrow channel would have immediately overwhelmed them. The Egyptians fled from the enclosing walls of water toward the western bank, but the waters kept converging until their depth completely covered all the war chariots and the cavalrymen belonging to Pharaoh\'92s military forces; not so much as one of them was let remain.\
It is obvious that such an overwhelming inundation would be impossible in a marsh. Moreover, in a shallow marsh dead bodies would not wash up on the shore, as actually took place, so that \'93Israel got to see the Egyptians dead on the seashore.\'94 \'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/59/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 14:22-31}}; MAP and PICTURE, Vol.\'a01, p.\'a0537.\
