\f2\i\b \cf2 Waters \'93congealed.\'94
\f0\i0\b0 \'a0According to the Bible description, the surging waters were congealed to let Israel pass through. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/60/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 15:8}}) This word \'93congealed\'94 is used in the\'a0
\f1\i American Standard Version,
\f0\i0 \'a0the\'a0
\f1\i King James Version,
\f0\i0 \'a0and translations by J.\'a0N.\'a0Darby, I.\'a0Leeser, R.\'a0Knox, and J.\'a0Rotherham. As defined in\'a0
\f1\i Webster\'92s Third New International Dictionary
\f0\i0 \'a0(1981), congeal means \'93to change from a fluid to a solid state by or as if by cold\'a0.\'a0.\'a0.\'a0: freeze\'a0.\'a0.\'a0.\'a0: to make (a liquid) viscid or of a consistency like jelly: curdle, coagulate.\'94 The Hebrew word here translated \'93congealed\'94 is used in\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/61/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Job 10:10}}\'a0with regard to curdling milk. Therefore, it does not of necessity mean that the walls of water were frozen solid, but that the consistency of the congealed substance may have been like gelatin or curds. Nothing visible was holding back the waters of the Red Sea on each side of the Israelites, hence the water had the appearance of being congealed, stiffened, curdled, or thickened so that it could remain standing like a wall on each side and not collapse in an inundation upon the Israelites, to their destruction. This was how they looked to Moses when a strong E wind divided the waters and dried up the basin so that it was not miry, nor frozen, but was easily traversable by the multitude.\
The pathway opened in the sea was wide enough that the Israelites, numbering possibly three million, could all cross to the eastern banks by morning. Then the congealed waters began to be released and to move in from either side, surging and overwhelming the Egyptians as Israel stood on the eastern bank contemplating Jehovah\'92s unparalleled deliverance of an entire nation from a world power. They realized the literal fulfillment of Moses\'92 words: \'93The Egyptians whom you do see today you will not see again, no, never again.\'94 \'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/62/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 14:13}}.\
So by a spectacular display of power Jehovah exalted his name and delivered Israel. Safe on the E shore of the Red Sea, Moses led the sons of Israel in a song, while his sister Miriam, the prophetess, took a tambourine in her hand and led all the women with tambourines and in dances, responding in song to the men. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/63/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 15:1,}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/63/1"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 \'a020,\'a021}}) A complete separation of Israel from their foes had been effected. When they went out from Egypt they were not allowed to suffer harm from man or beast; no dog even snarled at the Israelites or moved its tongue against them. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/64/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Ex 11:7}}) While the\'a0\cb4 \strokec5 Exodus\cb3 \strokec2 \'a0narrative does not mention that Pharaoh personally went into the sea with his military forces and was destroyed,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200001458/65/0"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Psalm 136:15}}\'a0does state that Jehovah \'93shook off Pharaoh and his military force into the Red Sea.\'94\
